# Practical 7 – HBase Installation & Working (Absolute Beginner Guide)

## Step 1: Open Ubuntu (WSL)

- Click **Start Menu**.
- Search **Ubuntu**.
- Open **Ubuntu**.
- A black terminal window will appear.

> Every command below is typed in this Ubuntu terminal unless mentioned otherwise.

↓

## Step 2: Download HBase

In the Ubuntu terminal, type:

```bash
wget https://archive.apache.org/dist/hbase/2.4.17/hbase-2.4.17-bin.tar.gz
```

Press **Enter**.

Wait until downloading finishes.

↓

## Step 3: Extract HBase

In the same Ubuntu terminal, type:

```bash
tar -xvzf hbase-2.4.17-bin.tar.gz
```

Press **Enter**.

After extraction, rename the folder.

Type:

```bash
mv hbase-2.4.17 hbase
```

Press **Enter**.

↓

## Step 4: Open Bash Configuration File

In the same Ubuntu terminal, type:

```bash
nano ~/.bashrc
```

Press **Enter**.

The **Nano Editor** opens.

Go to the bottom of the file.

Add:

```bash
export HBASE_HOME=~/hbase
export PATH=$PATH:$HBASE_HOME/bin
export JAVA_HOME=/usr/lib/jvm/java-17-openjdk-amd64
export PATH=$PATH:$JAVA_HOME/bin
```

Save:

- Ctrl + O
- Enter
- Ctrl + X

Back in the Ubuntu terminal, type:

```bash
source ~/.bashrc
```

Press **Enter**.

↓

## Step 5: Configure HBase

Still in the Ubuntu terminal, type:

```bash
nano ~/hbase/conf/hbase-site.xml
```

Press **Enter**.

Nano Editor opens.

Delete the existing content between `<configuration>` tags (if needed) and paste the following:

```xml
<configuration>
    <property>
        <name>hbase.rootdir</name>
        <value>file:///home/dev0/hbase_data</value>
    </property>
</configuration>
```

Save:

- Ctrl + O
- Enter
- Ctrl + X

↓

## Step 6: Start HBase

Back in the Ubuntu terminal, type:

```bash
start-hbase.sh
```

Press **Enter**.

Wait until HBase starts.

↓

## Step 7: Open HBase Shell

Still in the Ubuntu terminal, type:

```bash
hbase shell
```

Press **Enter**.

Now the screen changes.

You are **no longer in the Ubuntu terminal**.

You are inside the **HBase Shell**.

Every command below is typed inside the **HBase Shell**.

↓

## Step 8: Create a Table

Type:

```bash
create 'student', 'info'
```

Press **Enter**.

A table named **student** is created.

↓

## Step 9: Insert First Student

Type:

```bash
put 'student', '1', 'info:name', 'Alice'
```

Press **Enter**.

↓

Type:

```bash
put 'student', '1', 'info:age', '22'
```

Press **Enter**.

↓

## Step 10: Insert Second Student

Type:

```bash
put 'student', '2', 'info:name', 'Bob'
```

Press **Enter**.

↓

Type:

```bash
put 'student', '2', 'info:age', '24'
```

Press **Enter**.

↓

## Step 11: Display All Records

Still inside the **HBase Shell**, type:

```bash
scan 'student'
```

Press **Enter**.

All student records will be displayed.

↓

## Step 12: Display Only Student 1

Still inside the **HBase Shell**, type:

```bash
get 'student', '1'
```

Press **Enter**.

Only Student 1's record will be displayed.

↓

## Step 13: Exit HBase Shell

Still inside the **HBase Shell**, type:

```bash
exit
```

Press **Enter**.

You will return to the normal Ubuntu terminal.

---

# Complete Flow

Open Ubuntu
↓
Download HBase
↓
Extract HBase
↓
Open `.bashrc`
↓
Add Environment Variables
↓
Apply Changes (`source ~/.bashrc`)
↓
Open `hbase-site.xml`
↓
Paste Configuration
↓
Save File
↓
Start HBase
↓
Open HBase Shell
↓
Create Table
↓
Insert Data
↓
Scan Table
↓
Get Specific Row
↓
Exit HBase Shell
